                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It's not just that more time played equals more reward.  That is pretty natural and impossible to avoid.  It's the fact that playing more hours per day is much more rewarding than playing in a more spread out way.
<br />

<br />
Let's say person A and Person B both play 12 hours per week.  Person A plays 3 hours per day, four days per week.  Person B plays 12 hours on Saturday only.  It takes both of them an hour every time they want to setup a group and travel to a hunting area.  Person A spends 1/3 of his time setting up and getting no experience.  Person B spends only 1/12 of his play time setting up and getting no experience.  Person A gets only 8 hours of actual experience per week while person B gets 11.  Yet they play the same number of hours.  It seems like this resting system will help to even out the disparity.  I'm not in the beta so I don't know the exact numbers and they may well be too harsh.  But in theory, it seems like they're just giving you a bonus at the beginning to offset some of that setup time.
<br />

<br />
Second, they don't want people rushing through the game too quickly.  So you have two choices.  You can either keep the resting experience and play less to get your experience, or they can throw it out and make levelling more difficult across the board.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Suppose I play around 30-40 hours a week which would require me to have at least 3 toons on a given day. Now I end up having to do three times the work... grinding, questing, raiding, tradeskills -- you name it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
So you'd rather it take longer to exp on your main character so you could focus on him? Because let's face it, if they take out the rested thing, the default experience rate is NOT going to be the well-rested bonus.  So you're just going to have to kill more of the same mobs over and over to advance on your main.  
<br />

<br />
And what's wrong with logging off and doing something else besides playing that particular game if you'd rather have just one character? Personally I welcome the idea of being able to progress in a MMORPG and still have time for other hobbies.  If WoW is as much of a massive timesink as EQ, I won't be playing.  It's unfortunate, because it looks like an interesting game, but I just don't have the time.  At least in EQ, I've reached the max level, so if I take a week off, or I have to cut my hours down, I can still keep up with my friends.  I know casual gamers are horrible and worthless and all that bullshit, but if the MMORPG industry hopes to expand, they have to appeal more towards the general populace who are neither able nor willing to spend 40 hours per week on a game.    
<br />
 
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">With this time limit, now what do we do when all of our tanks and healers are too "tired" and we're 3/4 of the way through?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The patch message said that if you were tired you got an experience penalty, not that you couldn't play.  Last time I checked, raids weren't for experience anyway.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=317219" target="_blank" class="postlink">Mistress Regane Der'driu</a>
