		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><a name="37116"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Aerdyn</span></span><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_offline.gif" border="0" align="absbottom" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /><div class="gensmall"><img src="images/ranks/rank_1.gif" alt="Enchanter" title="Enchanter" border="0" /><br />Enchanter</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Joined:&nbsp;12 Feb 2004</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Total posts:&nbsp;21</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Gender:&nbsp;Unknown</div></td>
                <td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=37116#37116"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Mon Apr 19, 2004 1:12 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: rest states</span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=37116"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">From what I have read, there are 4 rest states:
<br />
well rested (with like a 20-25% bonus over a mobs normal xp)
<br />
rested (normal mob xp)
<br />
tired(first xp hit)
<br />
fatigued(final xp hit)
<br />

<br />
The ONLY way to get to well rested is to log off in an inn.  I have no idea if there is ever a time when that is not an option, but I just wanted to point that out.  Normal rest in any other spot can only take you to rested.  
<br />

<br />
Knowing that, still seems like plenty of people would at least play through the "rested" state.  DAoC did something similar to this in the dimishing camping return where once you hunted in a spot long enough you mastered it and got less xp.  This is essentially the same thing.  
<br />

<br />
If the well rested state lasts for 4 hours (much longer than I would ever design it for), then I'm guessing rested lasts at least that long.  I figured it would be something like I stated above:  A 2-4-2 split where 6 hours of play is the cut off to a real penalty.  
<br />

<br />
Yes you're penalized after 4, currently but only in terms of what they NOW give you.  Before this patch, you made "rested" state xp all the time.  If you played for 8 hours before this patch, and 8 hours after it, you now make MORE xp (bonus for the first 4 hours).  
<br />

<br />
Also, they want every class to be able to solo for xp.  Grouping gives bonuses beyond a soloer (or so they have stated).  That means that many people will solo while LFG, then get into a group.  This is good and bad.  It will eat into the time they can hunt in whatever state they are in, but it also gives them a means to make some progress while not in a group (unlike EQ), thus giving them more xp than they would by doing nothing.  Also they could just tradeskill or quest while lfg.  
<br />

<br />
Also, Blizzard may be trying to make their own mold, and not fit into the one developed by EQ.  They may be trying to make every moment that someone plays be important to that person.  Breaking it down further, 
<br />
EQ is not a time played = power ratio.  I know plenty of people who can log into EQ, lfg for hours, and end up logging off.  There are also plenty of people who jump on raids and ride the bandwagon to their flags, and then jump on those.  Minimal time invested to achieve what everquest doles out as their highest rewards.  The very FIRST people to do such things had a challenge, and a rough time of it, but once people start throwing out what the encounters in everquest entails, the challenge is gone.  It's a formula.  The only challenge is getting that many people together, and having them follow instructions.  
<br />

<br />
In EQ, players shine most in normal groups.  You have a role and a part to play based on the class system.  It's obvious whether you play it well or not.  You cannot generally afford to stop paying attention, or barely do anything.  You can show mastery of basic class elements and mastery of tactics just by playing.  Time invested in EQ shows dedication and perseverance, but not much more.  It doesn't even mean you have more xp than someone.  In the mass combat system that eq has provided, if everyone pays attention and/or has done it before, and doesnt fall asleep, it's a matter of numbers and equipment.  Equipment comes from numbers, and there you have the eq reward system.  This is the system EQ has devised for its current population.  It doesn't mean that every future game will follow this pattern.  
<br />

<br />
I am very much a powergamer, as I always want the most optimal use of my time.  I also play often, probably between 30-40 hours a week when a game interests me.  I would be very much impacted by this, but I also don't mind trying something new.  I know I am disatisfied by what EQ provides, but because I have come back to it twice now, I obviously still like many things about it.  I am very much willing to see if Blizzard's tests on times can make the whole experience better for me.  
<br />

<br />
For those that love EQ, why even bother to leave?  Why consider another game if you really LOVE the one you're in?  If you like 95% of EQ, you're pretty much setting yourself up for dissappointment as any other game has to have 96% of the things you love.  Someone mentioned monotony related to questing in WoW.  Apparently they have been playing a different evercamp than I have for 5 years, where monotony is how you advance.  You have to defeat monotony to gain xp in everquest, especially through the 50s (and it was worse with the hell levels).  
<br />

<br />
New game, new rules.  If the new rules stink, it will be shown very quickly.
<br />
I still think the resting xp thing may be mainly for the beta as well.  If you're running a beta, you want EVERYTHING tested.  So it makes sense to limit the item that 80% of your populace is focusing on to try and get them to focus on something else.  
<br />

<br />
Thanks for keeping the commentary going today btw, I like it when this particular thread is lively as it makes me feel almost like I'm in the beta. <img src="images/smiles/icon_razz.gif" alt="icon_razz.gif" border="0" />  
<br />

<br />
Have a good day all, 
<br />

<br />
Aerdyn</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
